  "prompt": "Is the activity of money laundering prohibited?",
  "response": "Yes, the activity of money laundering is prohibited and illegal in virtually every country around the world. Money laundering involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through legitimate businesses or financial systems to make it appear as though it comes from a lawful source. This process is a criminal offense because it facilitates criminal activities such as drug trafficking, terrorism, corruption, and tax evasion.\n\n### **Key Points:**\n1. **Legal Frameworks:**  \n   Most countries have enacted laws and regulations to combat money laundering. Examples include the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** in the United States, the **Proceeds of Crime Act (POCA)** in the UK, and the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** recommendations, which set international standards.\n\n2. **Consequences:**  \n   Penalties for money laundering can be severe, including hefty fines, imprisonment, and asset forfeiture. Businesses involved in money laundering can also face sanctions, loss of licenses, and reputational damage.\n\n3. **Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Measures:**  \n   Financial institutions and businesses are required to implement AML programs to detect and prevent money laundering. These include customer due diligence (CDD), transaction monitoring, and reporting suspicious activities to authorities.\n\n4. **Global Coordination:**  \n   Money laundering is often transnational, so international cooperation is critical. Organizations like FATF and INTERPOL work to harmonize laws and improve enforcement across borders.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is universally prohibited because it undermines the integrity of financial systems and enables criminal enterprises. Efforts to combat it are a priority for governments and financial institutions worldwide.",
